ew Mideast Strains; The Palestinian leader's comments highlight the difficult task the U.S. faces in brokering Israeli-Palestinian peace</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>TEL AVIV—Palestinian Authority President Mahmoud Abbas on Monday called the U.S. envoy to Israel a "son of a dog," in a fresh sign of the dire relations between Washington and the Palestinians and the hurdles to peace talks.</Para><Para>The leader made the comments during a speech blaming Hamas—the militant Palestinian rulers the Gaza Strip—for a failed assassination attack last week on a senior Palestinian Authority official. But he also criticized the White House for its stance on the Israeli-Palestinian conflict, singling out U.S. Ambassador David Friedman.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>"You are a settler and your family are settlers," Mr. Abbas said of the U.S. envoy in the West Bank city of Ramallah in a speech also branding him with the profanity.</Para><Para>Mr. Friedman has <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trumps-pick-for-israel-envoy-helped-fund-settlers-1482280901">helped fund a West Bank settlement </ELink>and has been a vocal supporter of settlements in areas the Palestinians consider vital to a future state. He lives near Tel Aviv in the official residence.</Para><Para>The Palestinian leader's verbal broadside highlights how a long-expected <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-to-increase-aid-to-jordan-despite-opposition-to-jerusalem-move-1518602434">White House plan </ELink>for Israeli-Palestinian peace is likely to face major obstacles when it is unveiled, not least because of the obvious animosity between those expected to negotiate a deal.</Para><Para>Mr. Friedman had earlier Monday criticized the Palestinian Authority for failing to condemn violence over the weekend that killed two Israeli soldiers and one civilian.</Para><Para>A Palestinian assailant on Friday drove his car into Israeli soldiers in the northern West Bank near the Jewish settlement of Mevo Dotan, killing two and wounding two others before being captured by Israeli security services. On Sunday, another Palestinian attacker stabbed to death an Israeli in Jerusalem's Old City before police shot dead the assailant.</Para><Para>Mr. Friedman in a tweet described the violence as a "tragedy," characterizing the attacks as in Israeli territory.</Para><Para>"Such brutality and no condemnation from the PA!," Mr. Friedman wrote, in a reference to the Palestinian Authority.</Para><Para>Jason Greenblatt, an aide to President Donald Trump on peace negotiations, criticized Mr. Abbas's rhetoric and urged the Palestinian leader to focus on improving "the quality of life of his people."</Para><Para>He added: "We are finalizing our plan for peace and we will advance it when circumstances are right."</Para><Para>The attacks over the weekend were carried out in East Jerusalem and the West Bank on land that the Palestinians, United Nations and much of the international community considers illegally occupied by Israel. Israel annexed East Jerusalem after the 1967 Six Day War and disputes that the West Bank is occupied or that settlements are illegal.</Para><Para>The Trump administration in December recognized Jerusalem as Israel's capital, shifting from decades of U.S. policy and infuriating Palestinians.</Para><Para>Tensions are also expected to rise in the coming weeks as the White House plans to <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-says-u-s-recognizes-jerusalem-as-israels-capital-1512584043">move the U.S. Embassy from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem </ELink>in May, despite warnings from the Palestinians and Arab states that the shift could foment bloodshed.</Para><Para>In response to the Palestinian leader's comments on Monday, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu tweeted that the U.S. had stopped "spoiling" Palestinian officials, causing "them to lose it."</Para><Para>In his speech on Monday, Mr. Abbas blamed Hamas for attacking his prime minister's convoy last week as it entered Gaza. The Palestinian leader indicated he would take financial and legal measures to punish the Islamist movement for the explosion. The Palestinian Authority directs a large proportion of its budget to Gaza, although it has curtailed funding over the past year.</Para><Para>Hamas in a statement condemned Mr. Abbas's speech, saying the leader wanted to walk away from recently-stalled reconciliation talks.</Para><Para>Write to Rory Jones at <ELink type="webpage" ref="mailto:rory.jones@wsj.com">rory.jones@wsj.com</ELink></Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">By Rory Jones and Dov Lieber </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">Copyright 2018 Dow Jones &amp; Company, Inc. All Rights Reserved. </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item><Item subtype="primary" size="0" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/palestinian-leader-calls-u-s-envoy-son-of-a-dog-amid-new-mideast-strains-1521498281" type="webpage"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

